name: Olallie Creek
description:
Introduction

Mount Rainier will be instituting a "pilot" *timed entry system in 2024, from Memorial Day-Labor Day.

Some key points:

  • no reservation is needed before 7am
  • no limit on how long you stay
  • each vehicle must have a unique timed entry ticket, and must enter during that 2 hour window.
  • reservations are through recreation.gov, and timelines for when they open are on the website below

What this means for most of us: For canyons along the paradise/stevens canyon corridor, July trips need to be planned by April 1, August trips by May 1, and either plan on one vehicle only, or have at least 2 of your team identified (and plan to be in separate vehicles) -OR- just plan to enter the park before 7am

The Canyon

In the span of one mile, Olallie presents obstacles galore; there are at least 16 drops with two major rappel sequences and countless downclimbs. The canyon starts off with crystal clear pools and rock beds that change colors from rusty red, white, pitch black, to speckles of red and turquoise. There's an inviting crooked corridor, walls that grow over 100 feet, ferns that drape from the sides, and trees growing on top of large chockstones. There is a four foot crack where all the flow drains into a roaring chute of water, whiteout, and a siphon in higher flow.

The best repeatable location for a reference photo is from the bridge on the Eastside Trail at canyon exit.

Olallie is in wilderness and machine-drilled bolts are prohibited without a permit. All anchors are natural anchors.

Your group should come prepared with sufficient natural anchor building experience and materials, particularly if you think your group may be the first through this season. Some rappels have limited anchor options.

Olallie is also pristine - please keep it that way. Ensure your gear is clean and dry before entering. If you introduce invasive species, they can destroy the canyon ecosystem.

Approach

Ensure all of your gear is clean and dry before starting your approach. Olallie is pristine, and delightfully sticky as a result - do not be the one to introduce invasive species to this canyon Drive into Mt Rainier National Park proper via the Stevens Canyon entrance. A National Park Pass or entrance fee is required for each vehicle. There is additional parking alongside the road just outside the park entrance for those without park passes. Exit parking is just inside the entrance at the Grove of the Patriarchs parking lot, which includes restrooms. This lot fills up quickly in the summer so it's a good idea to get there early. You have the option of a shuttle car which cuts out 0.5 miles of walking along side a potentially busy road. Set up the shuttle (46.7560, -121.5634) and proceed hiking 2 miles up the Cowlitz Divide Trail.

Descent

Upper Section

Before dropping in, please brush off your gear to ensure you aren’t transporting seeds from areas near the parking lot into the canyon. Please be vigilant about not transporting invasives. For the upper section, continue on the trail until around 3600' elevation, then bushwhack down to the creek. The upper sections will add on an additional +0.6mi of creek walking, 6+ rappels, spicy downclimbs in flow, crystal clear pools, and beautiful rock beds that are speckled with red, white, and turquoise colors.

There are at least 6-10 downclimbs that can be done as rappels based on flow and comfort level that are not documented in the beta.

R1: 30' DCL - tree

R2: 30' DCR - boulder

R3: 90' Center - log spanning the creek

R4: 20' DCR - tree

R5: 20' Center - log spanning the creek

R6: 30' DCL - tree. In higher flow, the water forms a curtain that you can swim behind.

Main Section

Before dropping in, brush all of your gear off to ensure you aren’t transporting seeds from the areas near the parking lot into the canyon. Please be vigilant about not transporting invasives. The more technical portion begins at R7. If only descending this portion, veer off the trail at the third switchback (46.7723, -121.5693) and traverse/bushwhack to the top of first large sequence at 2980' elevation (46.7752, -121.5644). There is no evidence of any trail here

R7, R8, R9 are done in sequence down a large cascade.

  • R7: 120' DCL - Two-stage rappel from a tree about 20' back from the lip. Rappel or controlled slide into a deep pool. This drop can also be jumped from the lip right 30' or by downclimbing past a tree against the right wall right to a small ledge 15'. In high flow, check for hydraulics. Continue on rope across the pool, climb out near the pour over, and continue down to the next pool, which is partially filled in with large rocks.
  • * A 200ft rope from this anchor will get you to R9 anchor. However, the rope pull here will likely get caught in the siphon created by the boulders in the 2nd pool, so as long as the R8 anchor remains trustworthy, it’s recommended to use it.
  • R8: 60’ DCR - Sling around rocks in the 2nd pothole.
  • R9: 60' DCL - Webbing around a tree to rappel in partial flow. Rock sling from a boulder wedged in a pothole to rappel dry.

R10: (High Flow) 50' DCL - tree. Scramble up a path DCL and rappel from a tree in the center of the canyon. Prepare to be eaten by a tree, possibly upside down. Careful of the roots, limbs, and branches as you rappel. This rappel is away from the watercourse.

(Moderate to low flow) Find or build an anchor DCR using the many boulders or logs in the watercourse. Note that the creek bends abruptly left past the boulder, so beware of rope pinching which could interfere with retrieval from below.

At the base of this rappel, look back upstream and look for flow stone and some small stalagmites on your right. Enjoy the last bit of sun before you enter the corridor and the narrows.

R11: 15' DCL - boulder into the narrows. Walk through a gorgeous corridor with slightly slanted walls for about 50 yards. Don't forget to look back.

R12: 100' DCL - tree DCL.

R13: 200' DCL in MULTIPLE stages (Apparition Falls). It is the most technical part of the canyon, and in high flow can be very dangerous. The water here funnels into a narrow chute about 3 feet wide. There are many large logs, rocks, and pinch points that can easily trap ropes when pulled. It is advisable to do this rappel in 3 stages of no more than approximately 60' each.

  • First stage:

60' from a log DCL to the top of a large wedged log and other debris. At high flows, the concentrated water in the chute is very powerful and can be enough to knock you off your feet. Spray coming in from the sides of the chute result in very poor visibility. Stemming above the chute is ideal, but potentially difficult. Removing your pack and sending it down later on a zipline is highly recommended. It may be possible to redirect the line over a log DCR to avoid the crack entirely. At low flows, the chute is pushy but not dangerous, and manageable for most canyoners. It is preferable for the first rappeller to deploy rope from a bag as they go to avoid dropping a rope into the strainer.

  • Second stage:

20' webbing anchor around the large log/debris pile (room enough for 2-3 people comfortably, but beware of loose logs/false floor) to a bunch of jagged rocks in a flattish corridor.

  • Third stage:

50-60' from a log or rocks. Rap down a couple of small drops then through the final chute in full flow unless stemming above the water. Alternatively, this drop can be downclimbed and the final chute jumped. Be careful if jumping the final part because ledges protrude on both sides.

R14: 50' DCR - log

R15: 30' Center - log (aka The Mouth Washer). In high water, the stream flows directly over a large log and unavoidably douses rappellers in the face.

R16: 25' DCL - log. The pool below is very deep and can be jumped. Be sure to send a person down to check depth before any jumps. There is also a cool cave to check out behind the waterfall.

R17: 20' DCL - large tree.

Walk the remaining creek until you hit a footbridge (~10-20 min). There are some downclimbs and nice bedrock to walk on along the way.

Exit

Follow the flat East Side Trail DCR (south) for ~1.5mi back to your car. Near the end you will reach a junction, continue straight to return to the parking area. (The suspension bridge to the left leads to the Grove of the Patriarchs.) Expect to encounter lots of non-canyoner tourists on the last leg of trail; this area is popular on summer weekends.

  • Time and energy-permitting, you might detour to check out the Grove of the Patriarchs. It's an impressive stand of old growth trees. Cross the suspension bridge and follow the 0.3mi loop.

Red tape

Mt. Rainier has an entrance fee. 1

Background

A documentation trip was done on July 15, 2017 by Barry Specht, Dan Yeisley, Jake Huddleston, Jeff Bartlett, and Tiffanie Lin. Webbing was found on two of the rappels. Thanks to Luca Chiarabini and Tabby Cavendish for the additional background and support.
